<form id="Cloze" method="post" action="" onsubmit="return false;">
<div class="ClozeBody">
S&#x00E3;o Paulo is the <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan0"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap0" onfocus="TrackFocus(0)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="7"></input></span><b>(large/larger/largest)</b> city in South America and the third <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan1"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap1" onfocus="TrackFocus(1)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="13"></input></span><b>(populous/more populous/the most populous)</b> city of the world, with more than 10 million inhabitants. It is the economical capital of Brazil and a very 
<span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan2"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap2" onfocus="TrackFocus(2)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(busy/busier/the busiest)</b> place. It is also <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan3"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap3" onfocus="TrackFocus(3)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(rich/richer/the richest)</b>
 in culture parks and museums.<br /> <br />

S&#x00E3;o Paulo is centered around the Pra&#x00E7;a da S&#x00E9;, where there is a stone mark symbolizing the "point zero" of the city. The subway system is <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan4"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap4" onfocus="TrackFocus(4)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(clean/cleaner/the cleanest)</b> and <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan5"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap5" onfocus="TrackFocus(5)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="9"></input></span><b>(efficient/more efficient/the most efficient)</b> but covers only a few areas of the city, although extensions are being made. <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan6"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap6" onfocus="TrackFocus(6)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="11"></input></span><b>(interesting/more interesting/ the most interesting)</b> neighborhoods to visit include Jardins, Itaim and the Ibirapuera Park.<br /><br />


The main sights in the city include the different neighborhoods with their <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan7"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap7" onfocus="TrackFocus(7)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="7"></input></span><b>(special/ more special/ most special)</b> Italian, Japanese or Arabic influences. They have their own characteristic atmosphere and it is a lot of fun to just walk around, go to one of the many <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan8"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap8" onfocus="TrackFocus(8)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(small/ smaller/ smallest)</b> restaurants or have a drink somewhere.<br /><br />


Brazilians say that paulistanos (S&#x00E3;o Paulo locals) live to work and to eat, which is probably true. Food in S&#x00E3;o Paulo is the <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan9"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap9" onfocus="TrackFocus(9)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(good/ better/best)</b> in the country and rivals that of any major capital in the world. If you are there and like to eat meat, make sure you try the rodizios (barbecue) or feijoada (pork and beans - served only on Wednesdays and Saturdays). The pizzas are also extremely tasteful and a must-eat. You can find it from a <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan10"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap10" onfocus="TrackFocus(10)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(wide/ wider/widest)</b> range of restaurants from the <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan11"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap11" onfocus="TrackFocus(11)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="8"></input></span><b>(simple/ simpler/ simplest)</b> delivery place to fine <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan12"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap12" onfocus="TrackFocus(12)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="9"></input></span><b>(expensive/ more expensive/ most expensive)</b> ones.<br /><br />


S&#x00E3;o Paulo is also very much a party town. You can get stuck in traffic in the middle of the night when party animals return from their hunt.<br /><br />

Automotive traffic in S&#x00E3;o Paulo is <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan13"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap13" onfocus="TrackFocus(13)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="11"></input></span><b>(complicated/ more complicated/ most complicated)</b>, especially in main routes, all along the weekdays and gets <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan14"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap14" onfocus="TrackFocus(14)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(bad/ worse/ worst)</b> at rush hours (from 8 am to 10 am and from 6 pm to 8 pm). Laws to regulate traffic include a rule forbidding cars to circulate at specific week days depending on the final number of their license. On the weekends the traffic <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan15"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap15" onfocus="TrackFocus(15)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(good/ better/ best)</b> is with some complications in places where there are bars, shopping centers or other public attractions.<br /><br />


S&#x00E3;o Paulo has the <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan16"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap16" onfocus="TrackFocus(16)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="7"></input></span><b>(large/ larger/ largest)</b>
 underground transportation system in Brazil: the "Metro". It is not as <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan17"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap17" onfocus="TrackFocus(17)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="13"></input></span><b>(comprehensive/ more comprehensive/ most comprehensive)</b>
 as the trains in Europe or North America, but it serves most of the important areas. It is the <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan18"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap18" onfocus="TrackFocus(18)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="6"></input></span><b>(safe/ safer/ safest)</b>
 and <span class="GapSpan" id="GapSpan19"><input style="width:80px;" type="text" id="Gap19" onfocus="TrackFocus(19)" onblur="LeaveGap()" class="GapBox" size="8"></input></span><b>(clean/ cleaner/ cleanest)</b>
 way to get around S&#x00E3;o Paulo.
